On 7/20/20 10:15 PM, tytso@mit.edu wrote:
> Sorry for not responding on this thread earlier; I've been pretty=20
> swamped lately.

Better late than never.

I've found that truly interesting threads on TUHS, COFF, cctalk, et al.=20
tend to go on for weeks.

> Xiafs was introduced at about the same time of ext2; Wikipedia=20
> states that
>=20
>     "Initially, Xiafs was more stable than ext2, but being a fairly
>     minimalistic modification of the MINIX file system, it was not very=

>     well suited for future extension."
>=20
> The first part wasn't quite accurate.  It turns out that xiafs had=20
> the same bug as ext2, but ext2 had the necessary sanity checking so=20
> that it actually issued a warning when the bug was triggered, where=20
> xiafs just silently corrupted the file system.

Now I'm curious what said bug was.

> The real issue was that xiafs was mostly a one-person show (namely=20
> Frank Xia) and he suffered blowback when he tried to rename xiafs=20
> to linuxfs, which was interpreted by many as a marketing effort ---=20
> about as tone-deaf as Stallman trying to jawbone people to rename=20
> "Linux" to "LiGNUx" ten years later.

Hum.  :-/

To be perfectly honest, I hadn't heard of Xia-FS until I started messing =

with H.J. Lu's bootable root disk.  I started messing with Linux in late =

'90s.  By then, everything was ext2.

> And xiafs was technically worse compared to ext2, and ext2 had a larger=
=20
> number of developers.  So xiafs never really stood much of a chance.

That makes sense, retrospectively.

> Also, by that point, very few people were actually using HJ's boot/root=
=20
> disks.  Most developers had moved on to the MCC distribution by that=20
> time, since it was more comprehensive, and it was easier to bootstrap=20
> a working development system.

Ya.  It seems as if H.J. Lu's disk had largely fallen to the annals of=20
history by '95.  MCC and SLS had come and gone, being replaced with=20
Slackware and Debian by the time that I started messing with Linux.

> So to be honest, I had never noticed that HJ was trying to use xiafs=20
> in his boot/root disks.

I can't guarantee that H.J. Lu used xiafs for his bootable root disk.  I =

want to say that he was using the minux file system.  It's the base disk =

images that seem to be using xiafs.

I've found a treasure trove of old Linux disk images on OldLinux [1] and =

am messing with them in Bochs.  (Bochs is working out better than=20
VirtualBox.)

[1] http://www.oldlinux.org/



--=20
Grant. . . .
